<FIRST>r a AM-LATeachers     05-21 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Awaits Negotiators For School District</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Negotiators for the 22,000-member teachers' union met again Sunday with school district representatives to seek a solution to a week-old teacher walkout that has caused chaos in city classrooms Representatives of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Unified School District arrived around 8:15 p.m., more than two hours after <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teacher-Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> negotiators showed up for talks set to begin at 6 p.m., said <ORGANIZATION> UTLA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>. `` It looks like the other side is dragging its feet and trying to prolong this thing,'' Ms. <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> said before they arrived. She added that teachers were prepared for a second week in the walkout that began May 15. `` We'll have our teachers out on the line again,'' she said. `` They've invested too much at this point.'' Details of developments in recent talks have been sketchy because of a news blackout imposed by state mediator <PERSON> Draz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mrvichin </PERSON>. The walkout last week played havoc with education in the nearly 600,000 - student district Many students walked out of classes and some joined teachers on picket lines. In some cases, students were housed in auditoriums because the district was unable to hire enough substitute teachers to fill classrooms. During the 16-month-long labor dispute, teachers have sought higher salaries and more say in how the district's 600-plus schools are run. Teachers earn between $ 23,440 and $ 43,319 a year, depending on experience and level of education. The union wants a three-year contract with a 26 percent raise, including a 10 percent raise the first year. The district, the second largest in the nation, has refused to go higher than a 21.5 percent raise over three years. The strike, which began May 15, is the district's first since a 23-day walkout in 1970.
</TEXT>
