<HEAD>2 Killed When Homemade Plane Plunges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Planes Collide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NILES, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A homebuilt airplane crashed after performing in an air show Sunday, killing its owner-pilot and a passenger, authorities said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, 49, of <LOCATION> Berrien </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Billings </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 45, of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> were pronounced dead at the scene of the crash, said state police dispatcher <PERSON> Suzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hibberd </PERSON>. The single-engine, two-seat plane built by <PERSON> White </PERSON> crashed at 3:06 p.m. in <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hibberd </PERSON> said. Witnesses said the plane made a sudden left turn and plummeted about 300 feet into a field. White and Billings had participated earlier Sunday in an air show in <LOCATION> Benton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> was investigating the cause of the crash, <PERSON> Hibberd </PERSON> said.
