<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Journalists, Diplomats Expelled From Britain, Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Moscow British Embassy comment,
identification of Britons, other details; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> ordered the expulsion of 11 Soviets, and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> responded by ordering eight British diplomats and three journalists out of the country for alleged espionage, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said Sunday. `` It's a mirror-image act of retaliation,'' British Ambassador <PERSON> Rodric </PERSON> <PERSON> Q. </PERSON> <PERSON> Braithwaite </PERSON> told a news conference. <PERSON> Roderic </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyne </PERSON>, the embassy's political counselor, said <PERSON> Braithwaite </PERSON> was summoned to the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday night and told that 11 Britons would have to leave <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> within 14 days. The previous day, Soviet Ambassador <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Zamyatin </PERSON> was called to the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and told by Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fretwell </PERSON>, the deputy permanent undersecretary, that 11 Soviets were engaged in `` activities incompatible with their status'' and must leave in 14 days, a <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom, said <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had not planned to make public the expulsions and did so only after the Soviets retalitated. The spokesman refused to say what the Soviets were accused of doing, but the charge he used of `` incompatible activities'' is diplomatic jargon for espionage. <PERSON> Lyne </PERSON> said the Britons ordered expelled from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> were Embassy Second Secretary <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, Second Secretary <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Noble </PERSON>, Third Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, Vice Consul <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON>, Naval Attache Capt. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, Assistant Naval Attache Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, Assistant Military Attache Maj. <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakespear </PERSON> and Warrant Officer Laing Purfit of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> staff. <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover-James </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Angus </PERSON> <PERSON> Roxburgh </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> also were give two weeks to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lyne </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Roxburgh </PERSON> called the action `` ludicrous, almost too silly to comment on.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> refused to identify the Soviets expelled. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> ITN </ORGANIZATION> radio reported the Soviets were caught spying on military installations. Press Association, the domestic British news agency, quoted unidentified diplomats as saying those expelled from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> include Soviet journalists. The expulsions of British and Soviet nationals are the first since the two countries expelled 31 of each other's citizens four years ago. The 1985 dispute began when <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> ordered 25 Soviets to leave after they were identified as secret agents by Soviet defector <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordievsky </PERSON>. In addition to the 11 Britons ordered expelled Saturday, <PERSON> Lyne </PERSON> said three British diplomats who had already completed their tours of assignment in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last year were declared `` persona non grata'' by the Soviets, meaning they can not return. <PERSON> Zamyatin </PERSON> also was told Friday that three former staff members at the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> could not come back to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lyne </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
