<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Students Say Government Issues Ultimatum To Leave Square</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD background, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Students occupying <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in violation of martial law said Sunday Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> ordered them to leave the square by dawn Monday or face a military attack. Troops occupied major state-run news organizations. Soldiers set up roadblocks around <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, presumably to prevent more demonstrators from reaching the capital, and about 1,500 troops armed with automatic weapons moved into the train station. Troops occupied the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reporter said. Soldiers will be sent to major universities, which have been the center of the monthlong protests for democratic change, to `` keep order,'' <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> television reported. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> called the 27th and 28th armies into the capital Friday night and declared martial law in central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on Saturday to put down the student-led protests that have drawn hundreds of thousands of people and caused major demonstrations in other cities. He did not say how many troops were called in. <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, in a message to the independent student union that has led the protests for a free press, an end to official corruption and other reforms, said the military would clear <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> by force by 5 a.m. Monday if the students refused to leave, according to an announcement by the union. In a broadcast over the student loudspeaker system in the square, they also claimed <PERSON> Li </PERSON> told <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> jails to be ready to accept a large number of students. `` We call on all of you to come stand with us,'' a student said after the announcement. `` The students are very weak and they need the people of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to help them. Even 200,000 people can not withstand the army.'' A Chinese source said 60,000 to 70,000 troops moved into the city center by subway and followed connecting tunnels to the walled palace, the history museum and the Great Hall of the People on three sides of <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>. The subway was closed to regular traffic as of noon Saturday and remained closed Sunday. There was no outward sign of the reported troop presence and it could not be confirmed. Official media repeatedly broadcast a statement that troops were in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to restore order, not to suppress the students. But it was clear order could not be restored without moving the students from <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>. The widely ignored martial law regulations include bans on marches, class boycotts, distribution of pamphlets, speeches, the spreading of rumors, attacks on party, government or military organs and `` any other destructive actions.'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s hard-line stand toward the students appears to have forced the resignation of the more liberal Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>. Demonstrations in other cities continued Sunday. Tens of thousands of people marched in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, according to a Western resident, and police diverted traffic. Several hundred marched in the coastal city of <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION>, a reporter at a local newspaper said. The military failed to make an expected attack Saturday night on 200,000 students and supporters who kept all-night vigil in Tiananmen Square. Many spent the night with gauze wound around their mouths and noses for protection against a tear gas attack and others slept on the hard stone pavement. Around the square and on roads citywide, citizens barricaded the way to <LOCATION> Tianamen </LOCATION> with buses, trucks, lightposts and anything else available. Thousands surrounded and immobilized tanks and trucks filled with soldiers throughout the city and in the suburbs. Local residents gave the soldiers cigarettes, food and water, and at one point Sunday 600 soldiers retreated several hundred yards. Troops set up blockades on highways into <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to prevent more people from moving into the capital. Crowds in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> and the surrounding area thinned substantially Sunday, but people began flocking toward the square in the evening after <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s ultimatum was announced.
</TEXT>
