<HEAD>Fourteen Drug Traffickers Hanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fourteen drug traffickers convicted by Islamic courts were hanged in two Iranian cities Sunday, raising the number of such executions since January to 637, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio reported. The broadcast, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, said the hangings took place in northwestern <LOCATION> Lahijan </LOCATION> and central <LOCATION> Birjand </LOCATION>. In January, Iranian authorities launched a nationwide crackdown on drug abuse. Under a new law, anyone caught in possession of even small amounts of any drug receives the death penalty. In the last nine days alone, 79 drug traffickers were hanged. The government has said that about 1 million of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s 50 million people are drug abusers, but unofficial estimates put the figure at twice that.
