<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Teng-hui </PERSON> on Sunday accepted the resignation of Premier <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo-hwa </PERSON> after failing to persuade him to remain in office, the official <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Yu </PERSON>, 75, announced Wednesday he had submitted his resignation to <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> to make way for a younger person and also to preserve unity within the governing <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Yu </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s premier since 1984, has been criticized for his cautious approach to economic and political reforms. Younger members of the party consider him a liability in a December parliamentary election. The <ORGANIZATION> CNA </ORGANIZATION> report made no mention of <PERSON> Yu </PERSON>'s successor. But newspapers said earlier the probable candidate is <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Huan </PERSON>, 72, the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s popular secretary-general. A decision will be made at a meeting Wednesday of the policy-making central committee, newspapers said.
