<SECOND>AM-Suzman, Bjt,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Legislator Ending 36-Year Career With Head High</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JOH1</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 For much of her life, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> has fought apartheid in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, sometimes the single lonely voice calling for reform. Last week she announced she will retire from <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> after 36 years. Here is a look at her work.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Back in 1963, a legislator of the governing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said of <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON>, who single-handedly represented the anti-apartheid opposition: `` Her days in Parliament are numbered.'' That would-be prophet, <PERSON> Cas </PERSON> <PERSON> Greyling </PERSON>, has since left <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, as has every one of his contemporaries except the indomitable woman he derided. Her days in office number some 13,200. Last week Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON>, 71, announced she will not seek re-election in September, ending a 36-year parliamentary career. Few politicians anywhere have served so long, in opposition to such an entrenched governing party, and fought so determinedly for their convictions. For 13 of those years, from 1961 to 1974, she was the only member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> speaking out against apartheid and campaigning for black rights. During a 15-week session in 1961, she made 66 speeches, offered 26 amendments and submitted 137 questions to parliamentary leaders. `` I do n't know how I made so many speeches,'' she said. `` I wrote every one myself _ that's why they were so lousy. They were not flowing speeches, but the contents have pleased me. When I look back at these speeches, I still think I have taken the right line.'' She has been lauded as `` the conscience of white <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was among those saluting her last week. Yet despite the accolades, Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> departed only slightly from her customary modesty. `` Without actually saying, ` I told you so,' it has been a source of considerable satisfaction to have been in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> over the past 10 years, when many of the laws I opposed when they were introduced have been repealed,'' she told her colleagues Thursday. She referred to the repeal of laws prohibiting interracial marriages, reserving certain jobs for whites and requiring blacks to have permits to be in whites-only areas. The Sowetan, the country's largest black-oriented daily newspaper, said many blacks `` owe her gratitude for the battles she has fought.'' `` The great pity is that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> simply was not good enough to have a person such as herself as the head of state,'' The <ORGANIZATION> Sowetan </ORGANIZATION> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> says her worst moment in Parliament came in 1966 when Prime Minister <PERSON> Hendrik </PERSON> <PERSON> Verwoerd </PERSON> was fatally stabbed by a deranged assassin, a few yards away from her. P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, defense minister at the time and now president, told her as he rushed past: `` You liberals did this. Now we will get you.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> did not speak to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> for several years, and their relationship remains distant. They served together in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> from 1953 until <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> became president in 1985. In one exchange in 1981, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> warned her not to break the law, and she replied: `` I am not frightened of you. I never have been and never will be. I think nothing of you.'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> also will retire in September. One of Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON>'s roles has been that of prophet. In 1981, referring to the unrest, she said: `` If it gets really bad, the government might suspend the law and rule by edict.'' In 1986, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> imposed a national state of emergency that remains in force. Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> predicted last week that blacks eventually will gain political rights and that remaining segregation laws will `` waste away'' or be repealed, `` though, alas, I will not be here to welcome their disappearance.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> was born <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gavronksy </PERSON>, daughter of Jewish immigrants from <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. She enrolled at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION> at 16, married physician <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> at 19, and later taught at <LOCATION> Witwatersrand </LOCATION> before running for <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in 1952 from <LOCATION> Houghton </LOCATION>, a wealthy <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> district she has served ever since Militants in later years urged her to quit, saying a <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that excluded blacks was no place for a genuine foe of apartheid. But she is convinced she played a vital role by `` keeping certain values alive.'' Her approach to politics was simple, she said last week: `` If you stick to basic principles, you do n't ever have to regret what you said.'' Other assessments of her career were less restrained. `` Only an extraordinary commitment to her political ideas could have carried her through the long years when she, alone, upheld the banner of civilization in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Business Day, a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> newspaper. `` She held a torch aloft in time of darkness.''
</TEXT>
