<HEAD>Eleven Vie To Succeed New Jersey's Popular Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eight Republicans and three Democrats are fighting in party primaries to emerge from the shadow of Gov. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON>, widely credited with pumping pride into a state that was long a favored target of standup comics. But <PERSON> Kean </PERSON>, a Republican who is barred by law from seeking a third consecutive term, remains a central figure in the campaign, especially among <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidates who vying to inherit his mantle. A millionaire from an old and influential <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> family, <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> won office in 1981 by the narrowest margin in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> history, defeating Democratic Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON> by less than one-twelfth of 1 percent of the vote. By 1985, his popularity had soared and he won a second term by the widest margin in state history, getting 62 percent of the black vote and widespread support among labor and Democrats. While the national Republican party grew more conservative under <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> advanced a moderate doctrine and urged the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> to bring women, blacks and other minorities into its fold. He rose to national prominence, delivering the keynote address at the Republican National Convention last year and winning praise from Presidents <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his education initiatives. And he has been an unabashed <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> booster, appearing on television commercials that tout the Garden State as an exciting place to visit _ a novel thought for most Americans. His popularity in a state where Democrats far outnumber Republicans makes him a tough act to follow. `` It's just like <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> trying to succeed <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. You have enormously huge shoes to fill,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, a Washington-based consultant who is running Republican Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>'s campaign. <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> was the first <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> governor to use television to build a public image that reached beyond the state's borders Television is playing a crucial role in the primary, and candidates are spending millions to broadcast their messages in the nation's most expensive television markets. Although only about 400,000 members of each party are expected to cast primary ballots, candidates will pour more than $ 7 million into television advertising during the three weeks before the June 6 primary. When <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> took office, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> staggered under economic stagnation, high unemployment rates and serious budget problems. For most of his term, <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> rode an economic boom. He doubled the size of the state budget during years when the treasury overflowed with $ 1 billion surpluses. But the good times came to an abrupt halt before the primary season. A predicted shortfall for next year grew to $ 500 million. Some budget analysts believe the gap could be as wide as $ 700 million. Soaring auto insurance rates have dominated the primary race, followed by debates over how to lower high local property tax rates and whether state taxes should be increased to solve the budget crisis. Growing traffic problems, congestion and the problems of managing rapid growth in the nation's most densely populated state also are big issues. Several of the candidates have likened themselves to <PERSON> Kean </PERSON>. <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>, former Attorney General <PERSON> Cary </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> are close <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> allies. <PERSON> Courter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> use <PERSON> Kean </PERSON>'s name in slogans that appear below their ballot lines, calling themselves `` Tom Kean Republicans.'' <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> are the most moderate candidates in the race. <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>, Assembly Speaker <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadwick </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardinale </PERSON> have carved images as conservative Republicans. Among the Democrats, <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, author of the federal Superfund law, is widely considered the virtually unbeatable frontrunner. Now in his third bid for the statehouse, he has run a low profile campaign, drawing criticism from his opponents for remaining silent on many key issues. In spite of the stacked political odds, liberal Assemblyman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> Mayor <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigmund </PERSON>, daughter of Rep. <PERSON> Lindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., and the late <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON>, are running spirited Democratic campaigns Three other Republicans are running low-budget campaigns. They are former state tourism official <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Rand </PERSON>, retired <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Blomquist </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolyer </PERSON>, an industrial arts teacher from <LOCATION> Matawan </LOCATION>.
