<FIRST>u w AM-Coelho-Dairy Bjt   05-21 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coelho-Dairy, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrat Had Dairy Industry Investment While Pushing Dairy
Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> owned an interest in a dairy management company at the same time he was pushing legislation to help maintain the profitability of some dairy farms, a review of records shows. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority whip and third-ranking Democrat in the chamber, became a limited partner in <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> in December 1983, according to his financial disclosure forms. When he bought into the partnership with an investment valued at between $ 5,000 and $ 15,000, the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> congressman was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> livestock, dairy and poultry subcommittee. He became chairman in 1985, a position he held for two years during the time the controversial 1985 farm bill was passed. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s financial dealings have been the subject of public interest since recent disclosures that a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> savings and loan official purchased a $ 100,000 bond for <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> when the congressman was unable to come up with the money. Dairy Management Associates developed a computer software program for managing dairy herds, allowing farmers to determine things such as how much milk a cow produces and how much it eats, <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s aides said. The program also is used by veterinarians. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> aide, said the congressman was `` comfortable enough in his mind to realize there was no potential for anything that he dairy or agriculture committee was going to pass that was going to impact directly on that investment.'' No law or rule prevents members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from holding assets that might conflict with their official duties. They are free to craft and vote on legislation that could affect their financial interests. White House officials and other executive branch employees, on the other hand, are barred under the basic federal conflict of interest law from taking government action in which they or their immediate family has a financial interest unless they obtain a waiver. The top penalty is two years in prison and a $ 10,000 fine. In 1985, <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> and then-Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffords </PERSON>, R-Vt., introduced a bill that, among other things, would pay farmers not to produce milk at a time the industry was beset with The legislation, which drew the ire of consumer and milk-user groups, was described by <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> as a way to ease some producers out of dairying while retaining profitability for the rest. Ultimately, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed legislation that called for modest cuts in the price support program, but authorized federally subsidized buy-outs of entire dairy herds. <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION>, a self-styled consumer lobby who fought <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> on dairy price support measures in 1985, said it stood to reason that if dairy farmers stay healthy they might be able to afford to buy computer software programs to manage herds. She said she had no idea of <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s investment at the time. One argument for exempting <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from conflict-of-interest statutes is that lawmakers must publicly disclose their holdings so voters can decide whether an official is acting for personal enrichment. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> listed his holding as <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> in 1983. In four following years, the entry was less descriptive. He simply stated on his financial disclosure forms that he had an interest in `` DMA -LRB- a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> limited partnership -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> put his assets, including his <ORGANIZATION> DMA </ORGANIZATION> interest, in a blind trust last June. <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON> said <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> does not fill out his forms personally and speculated that an aide called the company by its acronym, a pattern repeated annually. Partnership records on file in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ the most recent was Jan. 18, 1985 _ show <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s general partner in <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> was <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nash </PERSON>, who formerly worked for <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s accountant The company address was the same as the accountant's office in <LOCATION> Merced </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s aide, said the congressman knew <PERSON> Nash </PERSON>, but not He said <ORGANIZATION> Dairy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> has not had an office for several years. Another limited partner in Dairy Management is <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, the former aide to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, a close friend of <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s, resigned last week after an outpouring of criticism over a newspaper story detailing his attack on a woman in 1973.
