<FIRST>r w AM-AIDSDrugs     05-21 0931</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Drugs,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grassroots Concept Gaining Momentum in AIDS Drug Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A novel, grassroots concept in drug testing pioneered by AIDS victims and their doctors is gaining momentum and soon may see its first victory with widely expected government approval of a treatment for a lethal AIDS-related pneumonia. Far from the ivory towers of academic medical centers, the testing is being conducted in a few inner cities hard hit by the disease where local AIDS doctors and their patients search together to find treatments that work and disgard those that do n't. These community programs _ the two major ones are in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> _ were begun by AIDS patients and physicians frustrated by the slow pace of academic and government research to turn out a cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome and its deadly complications. `` People with AIDS just decided to do it themselves,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hannon </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION>, which operates out of an old loft building in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> where participating doctors administer experimental therapies to AIDS patients. Research data gathered by the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> group and the <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consortium </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> on an aerosol version of the drug pentamidine pursuaded a <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> advisory committee earlier this month to recommend approval of the treatment to prevent pneumocystis carinii pneumonia. The lung ailment kills 60 percent of all AIDS victims. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is widely expected to approve aerosol-administered pentamidine shortly. Pentamidine was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> as an injectable drug five years ago to treat those already suffering from pneumocystis. Many doctors, though, administered it as a spray. In February, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> expanded pentamidine's use in aerosol form as an experimental medication under government review. As a spray, the drug is delivered directly into the lungs where the pneumonia infection first shows up. In this form, pentamidine has been shown to help prevent pneumocystis infection. Advocates of the grassroots programs say the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> advisory committee's action represents a major breakthrough for the concept of community-based research and recognition that primary-care doctors can produce solid, clinical data in the routine delivery of medical services to their patients. The result, they hope, will be to help get effective therapies to AIDS victims faster. Community programs reach more people, they say, and so will be able to bring more AIDS patients into clinical trials, and with more participation, there will be more information with which to assess the effectiveness of drugs. The concept has won the backing of many scientists, drug companies and the federal government, which is preparing to award $ 6 million in grants to develop community-based research programs throughout the country. In addition to the federal money, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AIDS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in April gave $ 1.4 million to 16 community organizations starting reseach programs. Dr. <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> _ a cancer researcher, member of former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s AIDS commission and now President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s personal physician _ avidly supports community-based research as an extension of the work going on in university and government centers. These programs, he said, are free of the `` inherent biases'' of academic studies to exclude the sickest patients. A more representative sampling, which community programs provide, produces better results and without any slippage in quality, since many academic researchers sit on the advisory boards of the community programs, he said. He credits AIDS activists for pointing out the weaknesses in traditional research. `` The communities have stepped up to bat and they have tried to speed up the system. They came up with a constructive idea and I think it's a good one,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. He added: `` I hope they -LRB- community-research programs -RRB- spread out into other diseases. I think it's an excellent model for testing cancer drugs, diabetes drugs, heart disease drugs and others.'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON>, co-founder of Project Inform, a San Francisco-based AIDS education group, was an early proponent of community-based research and still supports it, but he says the movement has been `` romanticized.'' Few clinical trials are being done by community groups other than those in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, and most of the efforts are spearheaded by doctors _ not AIDS patients _ and so are not really the symbols of patient empowerment that advocates describe them to be, he said. `` It's an important part of a broader puzzle,'' <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think it's ever going to replace university-based research, and there's a limit to how big it can get because of the time it takes for doctors to participate.'' One mistake AIDS activists have made is in equating research with treatment, he said. `` The more pressure we put on the research process as being a way for treatment, the more we confound the research process, and the politicians find it a nice easy way out, instead of providing the money for health care,'' <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> said. Yet, the movement is generating `` overwhelming'' interest, said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Deyton </PERSON>, assistant director for community research at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases. When the government announced its $ 6 million program, it got more than 700 requests for information about it. <PERSON> Deyton </PERSON> declined to say how many applied by the April deadline, but a <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> source who spoke on the condition of anonymity said it was more than 60. <PERSON> Deyton </PERSON> estimated that as many as a dozen community-based groups are now involved in clinical trials for AIDS therapies. With more trials, he said, there would likely be more participation by Hispanics, blacks, intravenous drug users and women, who are now underrepresented in clinical testing.
</TEXT>
