<HEAD>Ishida Elected Head of No. 2 Opposition Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s second-largest opposition party elected a new chairman Sunday to succeed the party leader who resigned in an influence-peddling scandal. <PERSON> Koshiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishida </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Komeito </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s new leader, told members, `` I will fight to make the <ORGANIZATION> Komeito </ORGANIZATION> once more a party that is clean and trustworthy.'' <PERSON> Ishida </PERSON>, 58, previously one of four party vice chairmen, was elected to succeed <PERSON> Junya </PERSON> <PERSON> Yano </PERSON>, who resigned last week when prosecutors began formal questioning of a Komeito member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Katsuya </PERSON> <PERSON> Ikeda </PERSON> of Komeito and <PERSON> Takeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Fujinami </PERSON> of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> were interrogated by police last week. They are suspected of taking bribes from <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an information and publishing conglomerate. The so-called Recruit scandal has resulted in 14 bureaucrats and businessmen being arrested on bribery and securities law violation charges. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, who has acknowledged receiving political contributions from Recruit, announced last month he was resigning to take responsibility for the scandal. But his party has yet to find a successor who commands widespread respect and is untainted by the scandal. <PERSON> Yano </PERSON> himself was under fire in <LOCATION> Komeito </LOCATION>, the second-largest opposition party after the Socialists, for links to an earlier insider-trading scandal. More than 600 party members, including 56 members of the 512-seat <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representat