<HEAD>Parents of Slain Navy Diver Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT TOBACCO, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> have finally come home after nearly a year in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, now that a man has been convicted and sentenced to life in prison for the 1985 terrorist murder of their son. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>, 23, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver, was shot and his body dumped onto the pavement at <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> during the 17-day hijacking of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> Flight 847. The Stethems, both 53, attended 65 court sessions in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, beginning last July, for the trial of <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammadi </PERSON>. `` Nearly a year out of my grandchildren's lives,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> said. The Stethems returned to their <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> home Thursday night after <PERSON> Hammadi </PERSON>'s sentencing. `` We're very confident and really feel he'll stay behind bars,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Hammadi </PERSON>. `` So we feel our trip was worth it.'' `` They say time heals all wounds,'' <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> said. `` The pain has n't healed yet. And I do n't see it happening at this point. But this verdict has helped a lot.'' The first order of business was working in their yard and tending the rose garden Mrs. <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> maintains to harvest flowers for her son's grave at Arlington National Cemetery. A neighbor mowed the lawn while the Stethems were away, but a three-week lapse and abundant rain have given it time to grow knee-high. `` We must get on with our lives now,'' said <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>, a civilian <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> employee. `` We do n't feel in any danger. We've been victims already ... We'll never have <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> back.'' In the garage is their son's car, with a vanity license plate <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> obtained after his son was killed. `` ROBBIES,'' it says. `` We do n't drive it much,'' <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> said. The elder <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in 1953 when he was 17. He retired in 1979 but later returned as a civilian employee. Mrs. <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> also was in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, when they met. She now is a secretary at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. There are three other children: <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON>, 31, a mother of two, and two <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sons, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON>, 29, and <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, 23. `` I had actually tried to talk all of them into joining the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>,'' their father said. When the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> airplane was hijacked in June 1985, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was part of a crew of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> divers returning from a routine maintenance job at a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sewage treatment plant in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. They were on their way back to <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> now holds the same job his brother did. Why <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was chosen for execution by the Shiite Moslem terrorists remains unknown. Another diver, severely beaten at the same time, lived to testify at <PERSON> Hammadi </PERSON>'s trial. Two terrorists involved in the hijacking remain at large. Although the time they spent at the trial in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> did not provide answers to all their questions, the Stethems derived a certain solace. `` I had to be there,'' Ms. <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> said. `` I had to know what was happening. I would've climbed the walls wondering what was happening if I stayed at home.'' During breaks in the trial, she did volunteer work, typing at the dental clinic of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military base where they stayed. `` A lot of nights, I did n't sleep and walked around and called my daughter'' in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, she said. Her husband said he read a lot of books about terrorism. A security detail whisked them into the courtroom, which was inside a prison, and they sat with the prosecutor behind bulletproof glass. An interpreter translated. Now that they're home, the <PERSON> Stethems </PERSON> plan to visit their son's grave, taking newly cut roses from the garden and news of what happened to <PERSON> Hammadi </PERSON> `` This is going to be great, going this time,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> said, `` because I can tell him we just got one.''
