<HEAD>Former Autoworkers Rebuild Their Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> helped assemble cars for 16 years until he lost his job. Now he's helping former co-workers rebuild their lives. `` We've all been kicked in the teeth,'' said <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON>, 34. `` Now it's time to get up and go.'' <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> was a chief steward at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> until the company ended car production in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> last December, laying off more than 5,000 workers. The <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> factory complex, obtained by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> as part of its 1987 purchase of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, had been used for automaking for 86 years. In his new job as a career counselor, <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> is part of a network that is leading people to new jobs and trying to create employment opportunities. Some former workers say they realize the new jobs will pay far less than they earned at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, but they have to do something because unemployment benefits begin to evaporate in the next month. `` People are starting to get a little more desperate,'' said <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, 35, an ex-autoworker. `` People were relaxed at first because we had such a good benefits package.'' In addition to regular unemployment compensation, the package included a $ 20 million `` job bank'' from <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> that paid full salary to 2,200 senior workers for about three months. Workers with less seniority drew money from a `` sub-pay'' fund that provided $ 2,400 to each person. `` It's soon going to get to the point where the shoe really starts pinching,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> established at the local <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. More than 2,000 former autoworkers have sought help at the assistance center, and about 300 have landed new jobs so far, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. The center is staffed by other former <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> employees who have been trained to be counselors. The center has computer access to job openings in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. It also guides people to training programs at a technical school and provides a workshop where people can improve their math and English skills. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, 42, said that after brushing up her education, she hopes to get a civil service job. She had a chance to go to a Chrysler plant in <LOCATION> Belvidere </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, along with about 200 other former <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> autoworkers, but she and her husband did not want to leave their home. In the meantime, <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said she is coping with tight finances, although she says her unemployment benefits will continue until around July. `` We do n't go out anymore,'' she said. `` We do n't go out to a movie, bowling or even a tavern.'' Some people have started showing signs of alcohol or domestic problems, said said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Geiken </PERSON>, who helps run a `` listening post'' at the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> headquarters so laid off workers can receive emotional support. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is assisting in local economic development. `` We're not out of the picture,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> executive assigned to the effort. He noted that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is still <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION>'s largest employer, with about 1,200 people working at the company's engine plant. Workers, state and local officials expressed betrayal when <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> announced the December shutdown in January 1988, saying they believed the company had promised to continue production into the 1990s. The state even threatened to sue, but accepted a settlement that included the creation of <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s position for one year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> also donated vacant buildings for office and manufacturing space, and diverted profits from 1988 <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> car sales into a trust fund to help laid off workers with living expenses. The fund totals more than $ 23 million. `` The crisis part of it is over,'' said <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Executive <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, who noted that officials prepared to deal with the shutdown before it occurred. `` This was an unusual plant closing. Normally you do n't know about it a year ahead of time.''
