 40 years ago. The most successful primaries for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> have been those conducted by the opposition. In 1969, a three-way <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primary badly split the party and led to the election of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s first Republican governor since Reconstruction, <PERSON> Linwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Holton </PERSON>. In 1977, another Democratic primary set up a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> victory when former Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> staged an upset victory over Attorney General <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> in June. <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> lost that fall to Republican <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON>. After 1977, the Democrats stopped holding primaries and started winning elections _ in 1981 with <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> and 1985 with <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON>. `` When the Democrats quit the primary, a Democrat got elected,'' <PERSON> Rozell </PERSON> said. `` I think there's a connection there.''
