 The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> flag now flutters over a former boarding school seized last week by state officials who plan to make it a prison. But on trees nearby are tacked homemade signs depicting a cow in prison stripes and one word: `` Never.'' And there is still talk at the general store of stopping the state from building a 500-inmate medium-security prison in this isolated town of 800 people and more than twice as many dairy cows. It all started in 1983, when the <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> shut its doors and state officials decided to turn the building into a prison for drunken drivers. The project did n't go through and the prison was built instead in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, 40 miles away, but that was n't the end of the story. `` They came back with the regular prison,'' said <PERSON> Dorothea </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas-Vitrac </PERSON>, chairwoman of the town Board of <LOCATION> Selectmen </LOCATION>. To the state, the former Seventh Day Adventist boarding school perched on a windswept ridge is a place to build a badly needed prison without having to start from scratch. The 240-bed first phase of the prison, which the state hopes to complete in 18 months, is expected to cost about $ 25.6 million, including renovations at the school, said <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepe </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the state Division of Capitol Planning. The second construction phase is expected to cost $ 20.4 million, <PERSON> Pepe </PERSON> said. For the townspeople it's a battle to preserve the rural way of life in this little one-store hamlet, where the road in front of <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION> is blocked for 20 minutes twice a day while a farming family moves its cows to and from the barn for milking. It's the sort of place where the main road is a country lane squeezed between stone fences marking pastures that were clea