of aiding and abetting in the obstruction of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, shredding and altering documents and accepting a gratuity. The plaintiffs say there are more, 144 tapes in a system used by 100 to 150 people on the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> staff, and 32 in a system used by more than 300 in the Executive Office of the President, and that such messages are routinely destroyed. `` The fundamental issue in this case is whether the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EOP </ORGANIZATION> may authorize the routine destruction of information generated on the PROFS computer systems without complying with the requirements of the federal records laws,'' attorney <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Litigation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, representing the plaintiffs, told the judge in a memorandum. `` Plaintiffs' argument confuses the medium with the message,'' <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorneys replied. `` PROFS is simply a tool for conveying information.'' The government takes the position that the system is a substitute for calling a colleague on the telephone or talking with him or her in a hallway. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> told the court that `` the bulk of the information generated on that system is transitory and does not constitute record material.'' It said users of the system have been instructed repeatedly to make a printout of any information that legally amounts to a government record. Ms. <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, on the other hand, argued that the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> and executive office `` have made a blanket determination that, except in rare instances, the information generated on the PROFS systems is simply not covered by any of the federal records laws.'' If the judge denies the government's motion for summary judgment, Ms. <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> said the plaintiffs will file a motion to obtain additional information they need in order to show that `` the defendants have violated those laws by routinely deleting and ultimately deciding to destroy the information that existed on the PROFS system at the end of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration.'' Defendants in the case include <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, the archivist of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, who the plaintiffs accuse of `` failing to exercise proper oversight of the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION>'s and <ORGANIZATION> EOP </ORGANIZATION>'s routine destruction of information generated on the PROFs system.
