<HEAD>Sir John Hicks, Nobel Prize-Winning Economist, Dies at 85</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Economist Sir <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, winner of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Science in 1972, has died, his family announced Sunday. He was 85. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> died Saturday at his home at <LOCATION> Blockley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gloucestershire </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. No cause of death was announced. He was for many years a lecturer at the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universities </ORGANIZATION> and at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manchester </ORGANIZATION>. During his career, <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> frequently criticized monetarism, which advocates the control of money as the chief method of stabilizing the economy. The theory, which now prevails in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, argues that strict government control of the money supply is necessary to prevent high inflation. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> once commented, `` What is wrong with monetarism is that it tries to put all the kinds of inflation into the same box.'' His early work paralleled that of J.M. <PERSON> Keynes </PERSON>, who believed the money supply is largely unimportant in determining demand. <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> was was a pioneer in streamlining the general economic equilibrium theory, which explained the determination of prices and allocation of resources in an economy. It was for work on the equilibrium theory that <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> was awarded the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Science in 1972, sharing it with <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Arrow </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The prize was established in 1968 by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ