<HEAD>Ballet Theater Presents Three New Tharp Ballets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Choreographer <PERSON> Twyla </PERSON> <PERSON> Tharp </PERSON>, artistic associate of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ballet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION>, has some new ballets for the company this season. Instead of slipping them into the repertoire one a week, as might be expected, the company premiered three with a flourish on the same night, Saturday, at the Metropolitan Opera House. The first, `` Everlast,'' is set in 1919 and tells a story, like a charming movie of the <ORGANIZATION> Keystone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kops </ORGANIZATION> era, of a girl, danced by <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>, whose mother decides to marry her off to a boxing champ, danced by <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Day </PERSON>, for his money. The girl prefers dancing with the boys in the chorus. A waitress, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Adair </PERSON>, falls for the champ and dresses like a boy to get hired to work with his trainer. A couple of old busybodies, danced by <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, provide comic relief in an already light-hearted dance. They scoot in with potted trees in front of them, to spy on the oh-you-kid goings on and report to the mother, danced by <PERSON> Georgina </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON>. The music is 16 songs by <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Kern </PERSON>, chosen for lyrics that tell the story. <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Blazer </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Graae </PERSON> and <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON> sang them, on stage with <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dansicker </PERSON> at an upright piano. `` Everlast,'' at 40 minutes, is shorter than <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Astaire </PERSON> movie musicals because the plot is told by, instead of interrupted by, the songs and dancing. There is real dancing in `` Everlast,'' as a solo to `` Left All Alone Again Blues.'' We very much admire `` Quartet,'' the second <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> premiere, which uses four dancers and a recording by the Kronos Quartet of <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> music. It's in the tradition of modern-looking, plotless ballets to modern music like `` Episodes,'' which <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Balanchine </PERSON> choreographed to <LOCATION> Webern </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alessandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferri </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustamente </PERSON>, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> looked good, often dancing in unison, sometimes one couple's dancing echoing what the other had just done. Wearing crisp white shirts and black shorts, they moved constantly but never seemed frenetic. Miss <PERSON> Tharp </PERSON> is known for novelty and `` Bum's Rush,'' which we liked least of the three, is a novelty ballet, set on a vaudeville stage. Stagehands dance, so does a baggy-pants comedian. A truck tire with shapely legs and toe shoes sticking down from it walks around, gets between a ballerina and her partner or amusingly collapses on itself. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyman </PERSON> composed music for the half-hour romp. Our favorite part of it was jazz dancing by two men and our least favorite part slapstick by three men making animal noises. The three dances were premiered earlier this year in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, respectively. The evening ended with an older <PERSON> Twyla </PERSON> <PERSON> Tharp </PERSON> dance, `` In the Upper Room.''
