museum and the Great Hall of the People on three sides of <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>. The subway was closed to regular traffic most Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> and the Central Television Station also were occupied by troops, a <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reporter said. Only the English-language <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly business edition was delivered Sunday. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> television reported soldiers will be sent to major universities, which have been the center of the pro-democracy protests, to `` keep order.'' Vice Mayor <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Baifa </PERSON>, in a televised speech, said more than 200 buses and trolleys were being used as roadblocks around the city. He said city supplies of coal and liquified gas were running low and that the roadblocks hindered the transport of milk, eggs and other staples. Crowds surrounding troop trucks gave the soldiers cigarettes, food and water. Tens of thousands marched Sunday in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, a Western resident reported. Several hundred marched in the coastal city of <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION>, a reporter there said. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, a British colony that will come under Chinese rule in 1999, about 400,000 people marched peacefully to support the pro-democratic movement. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, thousands of Chinese studying in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> marched downtown to protest the declaration of martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The standoff in