<FIRST>r f AM-QuincyShipyard Bjt   05-21 0895</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quincy Shipyard, Bjt,0923</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indicted Junk Bond King Milken Rallies Shipyard Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX6 of May 19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When financier <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> addressed several hundred ex-shipyard workers, few seemed to care that he'd been indicted in the biggest-ever securities fraud case For them, this man was a messianic cheerleader who pledged to help get their jobs and company back. It may have been <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s high-school cheerleading experience that helped the junk-bond dealer from <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, who delivered a rousing speech to the crowd at the local Sons of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> hall. His subject was the Fore River Shipyard, which he promised to help the workers reopen with financing arranged by his former employer, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` When the first ship rolls in here on October first, I look forward to coming back and shaking your hands,'' he said. Ever since <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> closed the 182-acre yard three years ago, workers have dreamed of reopening it as an employee-owned business. The morale-boosting April 27 speech by <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, principal defendant in a 98-count securities fraud and racketeering indictment announced a month earlier, was only the latest twist in their saga. <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON>, a city of 85,000 people south of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, has a century-old tradition of shipbuilding. Old-timers proudly recount how they turned out the aircraft carriers Wasp and <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, the battleship <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and the first nuclear powered cruiser, the USS Long Beach. `` It's a family tradition for a lot of us,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Durand </PERSON>, 62. `` I worked there, my father worked there, and my son worked there. It takes skill and pride to pass it on from generation to generation _ and it's something we do n't want to lose.'' The yard was founded in 1884 by Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, an assistant to <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, and was managed after World War II by <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, father of the late president. For the first 75 years, it thrived on innovation as wood gave way to steel and sails to coal and oil. When the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> shrank after 1945, the yard began a long decline, slipping from a wartime peak of 16,000 employees to 5,000 in 1985 and 1,000 when it closed in May 1986. The next year, <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> sold the yard and several buildings for $ 49.5 million to the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, a quasi-public agency responsible for cleaning polluted <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. With support from Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> MWRA </ORGANIZATION> began negotiating a lease with the workers, who formed <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But the workers were frustrated for two years as negotiations foundered on such issues as hazardous waste liability and the <ORGANIZATION> MWRA </ORGANIZATION>'s desire to use some of the yard for its own purposes. The lease, finally negotiated last October, will allow the workers to use 70 acres rent-free for two years. After that, the rent will gradually rise from $ 100,000 in the third year to $ 1 million in the seventh. To keep the workers' dream alive, the state has pumped nearly $ 500,000 into the project. Although most of the former <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> employees have found new jobs, nearly 1,000 have signed cards saying they would like to return to work at <LOCATION> Fore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gwyn </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> manager who is president of <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilders </ORGANIZATION>, said he has talked with ship owners about potential contracts and is optimistic the yard could begin building and repairing vessels again in October. The plan hinges, however, on financing from <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>, known for its ability to raise huge amounts of money through the sale of high-yield debt securities. Commonly known as junk bonds, the securities are considered riskier for buyers than other forms of corporate debt. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON>, a vice president in the investment bank's <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> office, approached the workers about junk-bond financing last October, shortly after the lease with the <ORGANIZATION> MWRA </ORGANIZATION> was signed. With <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s help, <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> worked out a $ 17.3 million package consisting of $ 13 million in commercial loans, plus a $ 3.3 million investment by <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and $ 1 million from the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a group of insurance companies. In return for their investments, <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> and the insurance group will receive a 33 percent stake in the shipyard. The remaining 67 percent will go to the workers through an employee stock ownership plan. If the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agrees to guarantee 80 percent of the commercial loans, the financing could be in place by June 30 and the first workers rehired a few weeks later. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> executives say that despite <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s appearance at the Sons of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> hall, he has been no more than a cheerleader on the sidelines since March, when <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> agreed to dismiss him as part of its own deal to settle securities-fraud charges with the government. `` Prior to the settlement, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> was very involved both as a supporter of the shipyard and as somebody who was intimately involved in arranging the financing and helping to structure the transaction,'' <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> said. But, <PERSON> Flanagan </PERSON> added, `` his role going forward is just as a supporter _ he has no official role either as adviser or financier to the shipyard.'' Nevertheless, some workers still have warm feelings toward the man considered responsible for helping start a flood of corporate takeovers that reshaped corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in the 1980s. `` Once the yard is going again,'' said <PERSON> Durand </PERSON>, `` I'd be glad to shake his hand.''
